There are two methods to leverage `yaml.v3` and its comments feature:

- build a `yaml.Node` tree by hand (tedious maintenance; precise value updates)
- parse a template into a `yaml.Node` tree (easy maintenance; harder to value update)

----------
**Method 1:**


Craft a YAML Node tree by hand:

	config = &amp;yaml.Node{
		Kind: yaml.DocumentNode,
		Content: []*yaml.Node{
			&amp;yaml.Node{
				Kind: yaml.MappingNode,
				Content: []*yaml.Node{
					&amp;yaml.Node{
						Kind:        yaml.ScalarNode,
						Value:       &quot;ec2&quot;,
						HeadComment: &quot;# This section is for EC2&quot;,
					},
					&amp;yaml.Node{
						Kind:  yaml.ScalarNode,
						Style: yaml.DoubleQuotedStyle,
						Value: &quot;&quot;, // &lt;- field value goes here
					},

					&amp;yaml.Node{
						Kind:        yaml.ScalarNode,
						Value:       &quot;vpc&quot;,
						HeadComment: &quot;# This section is for VPC&quot;,
					},
					&amp;yaml.Node{
						Kind:  yaml.ScalarNode,
						Style: yaml.DoubleQuotedStyle,
						Value: &quot;&quot;, // &lt;- field value goes here
					},
				},
			},
		},
	}

Working Playground example: https://play.golang.org/p/Z6iw29rHZXk

Output:

    # This section is for EC2
    ec2: &quot;&quot;
    # This section is for VPC
    vpc: &quot;&quot;


----------
**Method 2:**

Read a template of your YAML schema e.g.

    var yamlSchema = []byte(`
    
    # EC2 header-comment
    ec2: &quot;&quot;
    
    # This section is for VPC
    vpc: &quot;&quot;
    
    `)

And then parse it at runtime into a `yaml.Node` tree like so:

    var c yaml.Node
	err := yaml.Unmarshal(yamlSchema, &amp;c)

But as a `yaml.Node` tree - which has nested slice of `yaml.Node`s - you&#39;d need to programmatically find your field values so when you Marshal the config for writing, the values are paired with the correct fields.

For example, this _may_ work today:

    c.Content[0].Content[1].Value = ec2Value // dangerous

but not tomorrow, when the schema changes.

Traversing the map and looking for the field value `ec2` and then placing its value in the adjacent node would be the proper way.

[Playground example](https://play.golang.org/p/qiIrsaDkyfw) shows how header/footer/inline comments can be added to the schema e.g.

    # This section is for EC2
    ec2: &quot;&quot;          # &lt;-- place user input here
    # footer EC2
    
    # This section is for VPC
    vpc: &quot;&quot;

